    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>Born on October 30, 1906, in Durand, a railroad center, Cleland B. Wyllie worked for two years for the Grand Trunk and Western Railroad prior to enrolling at the University of Michigan in the fall of 1926.</p>
      <p>After earning his bachelor's degree in 1930, he began his long career as journalist, first as telegraph editor for the <title render="italic">Owosso Argus Press</title>. He served in that post for five years before becoming editor of the <title render="italic">Durand Express</title>, a weekly newspaper. In 1937, Wyllie returned to the <title render="italic">Owosso Argus Press</title> as telegraph editor, and served in that post until becoming assistant editor of the U-M News Service in 1942.</p>
      <p>Following a leave of absence from the U-M while serving in the U.S. Army from 1943 to 1945, Wyllie returned to Ann Arbor to assume his former duties. A year later he was promoted to editor of the U-M News Service. Wyllie's title was changed to managing editor in 1956 and, in 1962, he became assistant director of media relations for mass media. In 1965, his title was changed to that of U-M director of media relations.</p>
      <p>Wyllie was a member of the Michigan Press Association, the Detroit Press Club, the University Club of Ann Arbor, and the Lexington Group, an organization of railroad historians. He served as publicity chairman for Michigan Week in 1970 and 1971.</p>
      <p>Wyllie died early July, 1979.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The collection is arranged into five series: Correspondence; Writings; Railroads; Miscellaneous; and Scrapbooks. Much of the collection relates to Wyllie's great interest in railroad history.</p>
    </scopecontent>
